Plenette Pierson had 21 points, nine rebounds and
two blocks to pace e Texas Tech (No. 10 ESPN/ USA Today, No. 8 AP) to a 70-66 victory
Monday night over Rice.
article.headline: Pierson scores  21 points for Texas Tech
article.linkText: Texas Tech struggles in victory over Rice
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Natalie Ritchie got a little redemption and a
little breathing room for eighth-ranked Texas Tech when she hit a
four-point play with 1:40 left in a close 70-66 victory over Rice
Monday night.

	   Seconds earlier, she sent up an air ball from 3-point range.

	   "Part of being a shooter is being able to put your last shot
behind you, if you make it or miss it," said Ritchie, who scored
seven of nine points in the second half.

	   "It just so happened that my girl backed off of me, and I was
wide open. I was just lucky enough that she fouled me, and that I
was able to put the free throw in."

	   Plenette Pierson led Tech's scoring with 21 points, nine
rebounds and two blocks as the Lady Raiders won their ninth
straight game since losing the season opener.

	   Kate Beckler led Rice (2-6) with 13 points.

	   Pierson had 18 points in the first half. She wound up making
nine of 17 shots and was 3-of-6 from the foul line.

	   Tech took a 6-4 lead before Rice went on a 13-2 run to take a
17-8 advantage midway through the first half.

	   Rice had a 39-36 halftime lead. The Lady Owls shot 55 percent
from the field in the first half. Texas Tech made 48 percent in the
first 20 minutes.

	   Jia Perkins added 14 points, Cisti Greenwalt 13, and Erin Grant
11 for Texas Tech.

	   Johnetta Hayes added 12 points, and Elisa Inman and Kim Lawson
11 apiece for the Lady Owls.

	   "I'm really proud that we made enough plays at the end to hold
them off and be able to take a win away, because I though it was
the most competitive game we've played since Louisiana Tech," Tech
coach Marsha Sharp said in Tuesday's Lubbock Avalanche-Journal.

	   "It's probably good for us to be on the road in front of a
hostile environment and have to make that many plays to win. We'll
use that as a learning experience to get ready for Big 12
(Conference) play."
